-- RAP Table I regression fixture (issue #111, #306) — n=98 companion to
-- ising_n42.qn. NOT the narrative Ising sample (see test/na/ising.qn, n=6;
-- test/verify/ising.qn). This is a CI-adjacent regression circuit: structural
-- fidelity to [RAP]'s reproduced row matters more than physical Trotter
-- semantics.
--
-- Target row: [RAP] (Stade, Lin, Cong, Wille, ICCAD 2025, arXiv:2505.22715)
-- Table I, Sec. VI-B, `ising` n=98 — published as 23 -> 12 rearrangement
-- steps (routing-agnostic -> routing-aware). Unlike ising_n42.qn, this row is
-- **optional / local-only, not a CI anchor** (issue #111's locked decision,
-- reaffirmed by #306): see
-- docs/neutral_atom/rap_table_i_methodology.md's "n = 98 (optional, local)"
-- section, which explicitly anticipated this exact file. Also unlike n42,
-- [RAP] Table I does not publish a two-qubit-gate-count / entangling-layer
-- breakdown for the n=98 row, so this file's own compiled counts (194
-- two-qubit gates, 4 entangling layers — see below) are a structural
-- self-check, not a published-number cross-check.
--
-- Structure: identical construction to ising_n42.qn, scaled to n=98. Two
-- Trotter-shaped steps of a 98-qubit nearest-neighbor chain. Each step's "ZZ
-- layer" is split into two explicit sequential `for` loops — even bonds
-- (0,1)(2,3)...(96,97) [49 gates], then odd bonds (1,2)(3,4)...(95,96) [48
-- gates] — instead of one ascending loop. Both groups are perfect matchings
-- (disjoint qubit pairs within a group), so `quon_na`'s ASAP dependency-DAG
-- scheduler (last-qubit-use tracking; ties to actual SSA wire threading, not
-- program text order) places every gate in a group on the SAME dag_layer and
-- only serializes between groups. Result: layers 0/1 (step 1 even/odd) then
-- 2/3 (step 2 even/odd) — 4 layers total, 49+48+49+48 = 194 two-qubit gates.
-- A single ascending `for i in range(97)` loop would instead chain every gate
-- through its shared neighbor and produce 97 serial layers per step — do not
-- "simplify" this file back to that shape (same rationale as ising_n42.qn).
--
-- Uses native `CZ` (not `Rzz`): `Rzz(theta) @(a,b)` elaborates to
-- `CNOT; Rz; CNOT` (frontend/src/elaborate.rs's decompose_rzz), which would
-- double the two-qubit gate count to 388 and break the 194/4 structural
-- self-check. `CZ` is in every NA target's `native_gates` and is not
-- decomposed. The single-qubit `Rx` layer is cosmetic Trotter-shape flavor:
-- `qubits(98)` iteration is a parallel (depth-1) construct, and single-qubit
-- gates are invisible to the two-qubit interaction-graph extraction, so it
-- cannot perturb the 194/4 counts either way.

fn zz_even_98(tau: Float): Circuit<98, 98, 49, Universal> = circuit {
    for k in range(49) { CZ @(2 * k, 2 * k + 1) }
}

fn zz_odd_98(tau: Float): Circuit<98, 98, 48, Universal> = circuit {
    for k in range(48) { CZ @(2 * k + 1, 2 * k + 2) }
}

fn x_layer_98(h: Float, tau: Float): Circuit<98, 98, 1, Universal> = circuit {
    for q in qubits(98) { Rx(-2.0 * h * tau) q }
}

fn trotter_step_98(h: Float, tau: Float): Circuit<98, 98, 98, Universal> = circuit {
    zz_even_98(tau) |> zz_odd_98(tau) |> x_layer_98(h, tau)
}

fn main(): Q<List<Bit>> = run {
    q <- (trotter_step_98(0.5, 0.1) |> trotter_step_98(0.5, 0.1)) @ (qreg 98)
    measure_all q
}
